Expressed in mathematical symbolism, Fourier's theorem reads as follows: 

y = f(x) = A_0 + 	ext{B} 	ext{sin}(n 	ext{x}) + A 	ext{sin}(n 	ext{x}) + A_1 	ext{cos}(n 	ext{x}) + B 	ext{cos}(n 	ext{x}) + 	ext{etc.} 

The latter from being periodic may be expressed as : 

y = A_0 + A 	ext{sin}(n 	ext{x}) + A_1 	ext{sin}(2n 	ext{x}) + A_2 	ext{sin}(3n 	ext{x}) + 	ext{etc.} 

where the B's and C's are suitably chosen.

For the purposes of the analysis, the expression may appear simpler if we write 

y = A_0 + B 	ext{cos}(n x) + C 	ext{sin}(n x) + A_1 	ext{cos}(2n x) + B_1 	ext{sin}(2n x) + A_2 	ext{cos}(3n x) + 	ext{etc.} 

Dealing with the three processes in turn, (a) by calculation, (b) by a graphical interpretation of method (a), and (c) by superposition, we commence with the study of method (a).
